    <fr:title text="Notes on event structures">Notes on <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">event structures</fr:link></fr:title>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>These notes are inspired and in large part derived from my reading of <fr:link href="staton-winskel-2010.xml" title="On the expressivity of symmetry in event structures" addr="staton-winskel-2010" type="local">Staton and Winskel’s paper on event structures with symmetry</fr:link>.</fr:p>
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:authors>
          <fr:author>
            <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
          </fr:author>
        </fr:authors>
        <fr:date>
          <fr:year>2023</fr:year>
          <fr:month>10</fr:month>
          <fr:day>26</fr:day>
        </fr:date>
        <fr:anchor>8407</fr:anchor>
        <fr:addr type="user">jms-00BS</fr:addr>
        <fr:route>jms-00BS.xml</fr:route>
        <fr:title text="A (pre)category of event structures">A (pre)category of <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">event structures</fr:link></fr:title>
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2023</fr:year>
              <fr:month>10</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>8403</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-00BN</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00BN.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Event structure">Event structure</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">
              <fr:link href="staton-winskel-2010.xml" title="On the expressivity of symmetry in event structures" addr="staton-winskel-2010" type="local">[staton-winskel-2010]</fr:link>
            </fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An <fr:em>event structure</fr:em> is defined to be triple <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (E,\mathsf {Con}_{E}, \leq _E\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> is a partial order of <fr:em>events</fr:em> partially ordered by the <fr:em>causal dependency relation</fr:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\leq _E]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {Con}_{E}\subseteq  \mathcal {P}_{\mathit {fin}}{\mathopen {}\left (E\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> specifies when a finite subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>consistent</fr:em>, satisfying the following laws:</fr:p>
            <fr:ol><fr:li>every downset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> is finite;</fr:li>
  <fr:li>every singleton set is consistent;</fr:li>
  <fr:li>any subset of a consistent subset is consistent;</fr:li>
  <fr:li>for any consistent subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in \mathsf {Con}_{E}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[e\leq  e']]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[e'\in  x]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\cup {\mathopen {}\left \{e\right \}\mathclose {}}\in \mathsf {Con}_{E}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li></fr:ol>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:p>The definition of <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">event structure</fr:link> only speaks of <fr:em>finite</fr:em> consistent subsets; these are extended to arbitrary subsets as follows.</fr:p>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2023</fr:year>
              <fr:month>10</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>8404</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-00BP</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00BP.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Consistent subsets of an event structure">Consistent subsets of an <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">event structure</fr:link></fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\subseteq  E]]></fr:tex> of an <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">event structure</fr:link> is said to be <fr:em>consistent</fr:em> when any finite subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> lies in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {Con}_{E}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2023</fr:year>
              <fr:month>10</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>8405</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-00BO</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00BO.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Configurations of an event structure">Configurations of an <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">event structure</fr:link></fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">
              <fr:link href="staton-winskel-2010.xml" title="On the expressivity of symmetry in event structures" addr="staton-winskel-2010" type="local">[staton-winskel-2010]</fr:link>
            </fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A <fr:em>configuration</fr:em> of an <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">event structure</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> is defined to be a <fr:link href="jms-00BP.xml" title="Consistent subsets of an event structure" addr="jms-00BP" type="local">consistent</fr:link>, downward-closed subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex>. We will write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}_{E}]]></fr:tex> for the set of all configurations of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}_{E}^{\mathit {fin}}]]></fr:tex> for the set of <fr:em>finite</fr:em> configurations of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2023</fr:year>
              <fr:month>10</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>8406</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-00BR</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00BR.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Rigid morphisms of event structures">Rigid morphisms of <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">event structures</fr:link></fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">
              <fr:link href="staton-winskel-2010.xml" title="On the expressivity of symmetry in event structures" addr="staton-winskel-2010" type="local">[staton-winskel-2010]</fr:link>
            </fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A <fr:em>rigid morphism</fr:em> of <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">event structures</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{E}\xrightarrow {{f}}{E'}]]></fr:tex> is a monotone function on events that preserves finite <fr:link href="jms-00BO.xml" title="Configurations of an event structure" addr="jms-00BO" type="local">configurations</fr:link> and is <fr:em>locally injective</fr:em> in the sense that for any finite <fr:link href="jms-00BO.xml" title="Configurations of an event structure" addr="jms-00BO" type="local">configuration</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in \mathcal {C}_{E}^{\mathit {fin}}]]></fr:tex> and events <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[e_1,e_2\in  x]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[fe_1 = fe_2]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[e_1=e_2]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:p>I have not checked whether the appropriate <fr:link href="jms-004K.xml" title="The structure identity principle" addr="jms-004K" type="local">structure identity principle</fr:link> holds for the (pre)category of <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">event structures</fr:link> and <fr:link href="jms-00BR.xml" title="Rigid morphisms of event structures" addr="jms-00BR" type="local">rigid morphisms</fr:link>. If it does not hold, this would suggest that a new <fr:em>univalent</fr:em> definition of event structure is needed.</fr:p>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:authors>
          <fr:author>
            <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
          </fr:author>
        </fr:authors>
        <fr:date>
          <fr:year>2023</fr:year>
          <fr:month>10</fr:month>
          <fr:day>26</fr:day>
        </fr:date>
        <fr:anchor>8411</fr:anchor>
        <fr:addr type="user">jms-00BU</fr:addr>
        <fr:route>jms-00BU.xml</fr:route>
        <fr:title text="A subcategory of computation paths">A subcategory of <fr:link href="jms-00BW.xml" title="Computation paths" addr="jms-00BW" type="local">computation paths</fr:link></fr:title>
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2023</fr:year>
              <fr:month>10</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>8408</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-00BV</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00BV.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Elementary event structures">Elementary event structures</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">event structure</fr:link> is called <fr:em>elementary</fr:em> when every finite set of events is <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">consistent</fr:link>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2023</fr:year>
              <fr:month>10</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>8409</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-00BW</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00BW.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Computation paths">Computation paths</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A <fr:em>computation path</fr:em> is defined to be a finite <fr:link href="jms-00BV.xml" title="Elementary event structures" addr="jms-00BV" type="local">elementary</fr:link> <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">event structure</fr:link>; we define the category of computation paths to be the full subcategory of <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">event structures</fr:link> and <fr:link href="jms-00BR.xml" title="Rigid morphisms of event structures" addr="jms-00BR" type="local">rigid maps</fr:link> spanned by computation paths.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2023</fr:year>
              <fr:month>10</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>8410</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-00BX</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00BX.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Rigid morphisms between computation paths">Rigid morphisms between computation paths</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A <fr:link href="jms-00BW.xml" title="Computation paths" addr="jms-00BW" type="local">computation path</fr:link> is clearly same thing as a finite poset. A <fr:link href="jms-00BR.xml" title="Rigid morphisms of event structures" addr="jms-00BR" type="local">rigid morphism</fr:link> between computation paths corresponds, however, to a <fr:em>monomorphism</fr:em> of posets (not necessarily regular).</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:authors>
          <fr:author>
            <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
          </fr:author>
        </fr:authors>
        <fr:date>
          <fr:year>2023</fr:year>
          <fr:month>10</fr:month>
          <fr:day>26</fr:day>
        </fr:date>
        <fr:anchor>8412</fr:anchor>
        <fr:addr type="user">jms-00BT</fr:addr>
        <fr:route>jms-00BT.xml</fr:route>
        <fr:title text="Event structures and prime algebraic domains"><fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">Event structures</fr:link> and prime algebraic domains</fr:title>
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:p><fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">Event structures</fr:link> are the same thing as prime algebraic domains; on objects, this has been proved many times, but I could only find the correct notion of morphism in a <fr:link href="abbes-2006.xml" title="A Cartesian closed category of event structures with quotients" addr="abbes-2006" type="local">paper of Abbes</fr:link>.</fr:p>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
  </fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:backmatter>
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" hidden-when-empty="true">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:anchor>21414</fr:anchor>
        <fr:title text="References">References</fr:title>
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="samstaton.xml" title="Sam Staton" addr="samstaton" type="local">Sam Staton</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="glynnwinskel.xml" title="Glynn Winskel" addr="glynnwinskel" type="local">Glynn Winskel</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2010</fr:year>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>21412</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">staton-winskel-2010</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>staton-winskel-2010.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="On the expressivity of symmetry in event structures">On the expressivity of symmetry in event structures</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Reference</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="venue">2010 25th Annual IEEE Symposium on Logic in Computer Science</fr:meta>
            <fr:meta name="doi">10.1109/LICS.2010.37</fr:meta>
            <fr:meta name="bibtex"><![CDATA[@inproceedings{staton-winskel-2010,
  author={Staton, Sam and Winskel, Glynn},
  booktitle={2010 25th Annual IEEE Symposium on Logic in Computer Science},
  title={On the Expressivity of Symmetry in Event Structures},
  year={2010},
  pages={392-401},
  doi={10.1109/LICS.2010.37}
}]]></fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>This paper establishes a bridge between presheaf models for concurrency and the more operationally-informative world of <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">event structures</fr:link>. It concentrates on a particular presheaf category, consisting of presheaves over finite partial orders of events; such presheaves form a model of nondeterministic processes in which the computation paths have the shape of partial orders. It is shown how with the introduction of symmetry event structures represent all presheaves over finite partial orders. This is in contrast with <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">plain event structures</fr:link> which only represent certain separated presheaves. Specifically a coreflection from the category of presheaves to the category of event structures with symmetry is exhibited. It is shown how the coreflection can be cut down to an equivalence between the presheaf category and the subcategory of graded event structures with symmetry. Event structures with strong symmetries are shown to represent precisely all the separated presheaves. The broader context and specific applications to the unfolding of higher-dimensional automata and Petri nets, and weak bisimulation on event structures are sketched.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="samyabbes.xml" title="Samy Abbes" addr="samyabbes" type="local">Samy Abbes</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2006</fr:year>
              <fr:month>1</fr:month>
              <fr:day>1</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>21413</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">abbes-2006</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>abbes-2006.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="A Cartesian closed category of event structures with quotients">A Cartesian closed category of <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">event structures</fr:link> with quotients</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Reference</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="doi">10.46298/dmtcs.374</fr:meta>
            <fr:meta name="venue">Discrete Mathematics &amp; Theoretical Computer Science</fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>We introduce a new class of morphisms for <fr:link href="jms-00BN.xml" title="Event structure" addr="jms-00BN" type="local">event structures</fr:link>. The category obtained is cartesian closed, and a natural notion of quotient event structure is defined within it. We study in particular the topological space of maximal configurations of quotient event structures. We introduce the compression of event structures as an example of quotient: the compression of an event structure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> is a minimal event structure with the same space of maximal configurations as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
